        </TableRow>

      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

    <Paragraph>Declares the language and culture information for an object element. The definition for the <Run FontWeight="Bold">xml:lang</Run>
 attribute in XAML is derived from <Run FontWeight="Bold">xml:lang</Run>
 as defined as a "special attribute" by World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) for XML. Language and culture information is potentially processed in different ways by elements depending on their implementations, but there is no default XAML processing of the <Run FontWeight="Bold">xml:lang</Run>
 attribute.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>Example Attribute Usage</Run>

    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>
&lt;<Run FontStyle="italic">object </Run>
<Run FontWeight="Bold">xml:lang</Run>
="<Run FontStyle="italic">rfc3066lang</Run>
" />
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>Remarks</Run>

    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph><Run FontStyle="italic">rfc3066lang</Run>
 in the above syntax is a string derived from the RFC 3066 standard that identifies either a language, or a language-region with language and region separated by a single hyphen. See XmlLanguage for more information on the values and format.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>The default value of the <Run FontWeight="Bold">xml:lang</Run>
 attribute is an empty string at the attribute level.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>The <Run FontWeight="Bold">xml:lang</Run>
 attribute effects and the value of the attribute are scoped to child elements.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>For elements that are subclasses of FrameworkElement or FrameworkContentElement, you can use the equivalent Language <Run>dependency property</Run>
 rather than the <Run FontWeight="Bold">xml:lang</Run>
 attribute. The <Run FontWeight="Bold">Language</Run>
 property will default to "en-US" if not otherwise set either through the property itself or through parsing the <Run FontWeight="Bold">xml:lang</Run>
 attribute.
    </Paragraph>

